text: Examination of Potential Exceptions to the F and S Biosynthetic Classification of Fused-Ring Aromatic Polyketides Robert Thomas*[a] The reported acetate-derived labelling of the fungal naphtha- lene g-pyrone fonsecin, two streptomycete dodecaketide a- pyrones TW93f and TW93g, and the streptomycete phenan- thraquinones piloquinone, murayaquinone and haloquinone appear to be exceptions to the generalisation that fungi and streptomycetes produce fused-ring aromatic polyketides by The majority of microbial aromatic polyketides (PKs) are formed through iterative Claisen condensations of a thioesteri- fied acetate starter unit and malonate extender units, followed by regiospecific intramolecular crosslinking of poly-b-ketoacyl intermediates.[1] A corresponding pathway for the biosynthesis of 6-methylsalicylic acid (6-MSA, 1; Scheme 1) in fungi was ini- tially proposed by Birch and Donovan in 1953[2] and subse- quently confirmed by a study of the mode of incorporation of [1-14C]-labelled acetate in the early 1950s.[3] The first investiga- tion of 6-MSA-synthesising enzymes was reported by Lynen and co-workers in 1970.[4] Scheme 1. 6-MSA (1), oxytetracycline (2) and viridicatumtoxin (3). Carbons are numbered in the same sequence as in their polyketide precursors; bold bonds denote intact acetates incorporated in these and in subsequent struc- tures; red bonds show acetate units in initially formed benzene rings only. different modes of cyclisation. A review of their 1) originally as- signed formulae, 2) [13C2]acetate-derived labelling patterns, and 3) modes of cyclisation leads to the recognition of feasible al- ternative chemical structures or biosynthetic pathways, which are in accord with the originally proposed classification system. A related concept involving cyclisation of PK chains was originally described by Collie in 1907;[5] following Birch’s specu- lative and experimental contributions, by the end of the 1950s the key role of the PK pathway in the biosynthesis of aromatic natural products had been confirmed by other chemists.[6, 7] In 1953, Robinson suggested the possibility of a PK origin for the fused-ring tetracycline antibiotics produced by strepto- mycetes.[8] However, it was not until 1983 (and the routine use of carbon-13 NMR spectroscopy) the tetracyclic ring system of oxytetracyline (OTC, 2) was shown to be derived ex- clusively from intact acetate units.[9] 2. Biosynthetic Classification of Fused-Ring Aromatic Polyketides Of particular interest was the unanticipated discovery that whereas three intact pairs of carbon atoms are incorporated from [13C2]acetate during the biosynthesis of the assumed ini- tially formed benzene ring of 2 by the bacterium Streptomyces rimosus (“mode S folding”), only two intact acetate units are incorporated into the corresponding initial ring of the structur- ally related fungal tetracycline viridicatumtoxin 3 (mode F fold- ing).[10] Such F and S labelling patterns provide an easily recognisa- ble distinguishing characteristic of fused-ring aromatic fungal and streptomycete PKs, for example polyhydroxy-naphthalene, anthracene and tetracycline derivatives. This finding was pro- posed as the basis of a general rule for the biosynthesis of fused-ring, but not (as discussed below) for monocyclic benze- noid PKs.[11] The resulting hypothesis has a number of useful ramifications, including the detection of erroneously assigned chemical structures and biosynthetic pathways.

In keeping with this classification, Bringmann and colleagues confirmed the predicted F mode of incorporation of [13C2]- acetate into the partially reduced anthraquinone octaketide chrysophanol 4 produced by the fungus Drechslera catenaria (cid:2) 2016 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim and other eukaryotes, including some higher plants and in- sects.[12, 13] In addition, they confirmed that S-mode-folded chry- sophanol with the labelling pattern 5 is formed by a filamen- tous strain of the bacterial genus Nocardia. Mode-F-folded chrysophanol (4) is probably formed by de- esterification and decarboxylation of the deoxyendocrocin an- throne thioester intermediate 7 (or its tautomer, 6) and subse- quent oxidation. Similarly, mode-S-folded chrysophanol 5 might form through decarboxylation and oxidation of an anal- ogous isomeric streptomycete carboxylic acid thioester inter- mediate (8). Interestingly, the Bringmann group also detected a third mode of incorporation of [13C2]acetate into chrysophanol by a strain of Streptomyces; they termed this mode S’. Whereas S’- labelled chrysophanol 9 exhibits the same modes of incorpora- tion of intact acetate units in both the initial and the second ring as does the S-mode cyclised product 5, it was found to use a different mode of cyclisation of intact acetate units for the assembly of its third ring. The initial rings of F-, S- and S’- cyclised chrysophanols appear to form by intramolecular aldol crosslinking of linear octaketide precursors between C-6 and C- 11, C-5 and C-10, and C-7 and C-12, respectively (Scheme 2). As the same structure is produced by different pathways, this strategy is sometimes referred to as “convergent biosynthesis”.

Scheme 2. Biosyntheses of [13C2]acetate-labelled mode-F-, -S- and -S’-folded chrysophanols derived from C-7 or C-9 partially reduced linear octaketides. ChemBioChem 2016, 17, 1 – 9 Following the ground-breaking genetic and enzymatic inves- tigations of Hopwood and co-workers,[14] our understanding of the mechanisms of biosynthesis of streptomycete and fungal PKs has made considerable progress (recent developments are reviewed in a themed issue of Natural Product Reports).[15–18] Key problems discussed by these and other authors include the mechanisms of ring closure leading to aromatic PKs by product template domains of fungal type I iterative polyketide synthases (PKSs) and the corresponding cyclisations by equiva- lent aromatase and cyclase (ARO/CYC) domains of streptomy- cete type II PKSs. However, despite extensive progress, many details of the modes of formation of F- and S-folded aromatic PKs remain to be clarified. 3. Monobenzenoid Polyketides The specific (F or S) biosynthetic classification of aromatic PKs only applies to fused-ring PKs.[11] Monocyclic fungal PKs are well established as having a single benzenoid ring incorporat- ing either two or three intact pairs of acetate carbons, corre- sponding to F- or S-folded rings, respectively. This contrasts with the dihydroxyphenylacetic acid lactone 10,11-dehydrocur- vularin (11) of the fungus Aspergillus terreus, where the ben- zene ring is formed from three intact acetate units, and is thus parallels mode S folding. These two metabolites were investigated by Xu et al., in an extensive chemical, genetic and enzymatic study of the forma- tion of fungal monobenzenoid PKs;[19] they confirmed the uti- lisation by moulds of both modes of folding. They also showed that the cyclisation regiospecificity can be reprogrammed by site-directed mutagenesis. In the course of cyclisation of conformers 12 and 13, the PK chain probably continues to fold until growth is complete. At- tainment of the target mode of folding might be facilitated by the stabilising influence of hydrogen bonding at the synthase active site. F- or S-type folding of a linear pentaketide might be based on regioselective C-2/7 or C-3/8 cyclisations with hydrogen bond- ing between O-7 of 12 or O-3 of 13 and their respective keto- synthases (Scheme 3 A). These two conformations are intercon- vertible through concerted rotation of their C-1/2 and C-8/9 (or equivalent) carbon bonds, as can be readily demonstrated with simple molecular models. Catalysis of the C-2/7 aldol condensation of 12 leads to cycli- sation with the incorporation of two intact acetate units (mode F folding), as in the formation of the benzoate ring of monocillin (10). In contrast, three intact acetates are used in the phenylacetate mode-S-type folding that leads to the fungal lactone 10,11-dehydrocurvularin (11). Examples of the latter S mode leading to monocyclic aromatic PKs of bacteria are discussed in a previous review.[11] These include diacetyl- phloroglucinol from Pseudomonas fluorescens and vancomycin from Streptomyces orientalis. In this context, it is of interest to note that the C-2/7 mode- F-folded benzoic acid lactone reticulol (14) is a known product of the bacterium Streptomyces mobaraensis (Scheme 3 B).[20] 4. Candidate Exceptions to the Biosynthetic Classification of Fused-Ring Aromatic Poly- ketides With regard to the validity of the proposed biosynthetic clas- sification of fused-ring aromatic compounds, very few possible exceptions have been identified to date.

Prior to the discussion of potential exceptions, attention is directed to another significant feature of fused-ring aromatic PKs. This concerns the relative lengths of ortho side-chain sub- stituents of the initially formed benzenoid rings. In fungi, a side chain with a terminal methyl or acetate methyl-derived group normally appears to be least as long as that of a co-ex- isting ortho terminal carboxyl or lactonised side chain. An ex- ception is in the fungal heptaketide pannorin (16),[21, 22] which is a naphtho-a-pyrone constituent of the fungus Chrysoporium pannorum. In the assigned structures of pannorin and its putative mon- ocyclic precursor 15 (Scheme 4), the predicted initially formed ring has a side-chain substituent at C-6 comprising five car- bons (C-1 to C-5). This is ortho to the terminal methyl substi- tuted side chain at C-11, which has only three carbons (C-12 to C-14). Its similarly named pannorin B (17)[23] is a closely related octaketide naphtho-a-pyrone constituent of a Penicillium sp., and has two adjacent five-carbon side-chain substituents; con- is biosynthetically unexceptional. Conceivably, sequently, pannorin B could serve as a precursor of the atypical hepta- ketide pannorin through elimination of the presumed two- carbon acetate starter unit of the parent octaketide (C-15 and C-16; Scheme 4). The atypical pannorin ortho side-chain-length constraint does not apply to streptomycete fused-ring products, as can be seen from the structure of the monomeric octaketide unit of the Streptomyces coelicolor bisnaphthoquinone actinorhodin 18. 13C NMR peak assignments and long-range heteronuclear cou- pling constants in the spectra of the [13C2]acetate-derived fungal heptaketide fonsecin led Bloomer and colleagues to conclude that its initial carbocyclic ring is formed by the fold- ing mode depicted for the g-pyrone 19 (Scheme 5).[24] This involves mode S incorporation of three intact acetate units in the initially formed ring, in contrast to the predicted mode-F- it fused ring polyketide fungal differs from the characteristic mode F cyclisation observed by Leeper and Staunton in their study of the origin of [13C2]- acetate-derived rubrofusarin 20, a structurally related fungal heptaketide g-pyrone.[30] Of additional interest is the finding by Ehrlich et al. that fonsecin and rubrofusarin co-occur in Asper- gillus niger with other naphtho-g-pyrones.[24] A possible alternative interpretation to that of Bloomer’s group for the fonsecin 13C NMR assignments is outlined in structure 21. The revised structure would be compatible with fungal mode F folding[11] and is in close agreement with the corresponding rubrofusarin dimethyl ether spectral assign- ments of Leeper and Staunton. More recently, Shaaban et al. described the isolation from a marine strain of the fungus Alternaria alternata (also known as Alternaria tenuis) of eight g-pyrone fused-ring heptaketides, including fonsecin and rubrofusarin.[31] The co-occurrence of these structurally related metabolites is consistent with a common biosynthetic origin by mode F cyclisation; this con- trasts with Bloomer’s group’s interpretation of the fonsecin NMR spectra (mode S cyclisation).

It is noteworthy that neither the archetypal A. alternata hep- taketide dibenzo-a-pyrone alternariol, nor its methyl ether 22,[32] or altenuic acid II 23[33] or altenuic acid III 24[34] conge- ners were among the products observed in Shaaban’s marine strain of this Alternaria species, although good yields of all of these metabolites were recovered from the initially studied al- ternariol-producing terrestrial strain of this fungus.[35] (cid:2) 2016 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. Furthermore, TW93f (25) and TW93g (26) are biosynthetically atypical fused- ring naphthalene-based dodecaketides formed upon expres- sion of the whiE gene cluster that leads to production of the grey or white spore pigment of a prolific recombinant strain of S. coelicolor.[25] The assigned structures contain, respectively, C- 8/C-13- and C-10/C-15-bridged initial rings, both of which un- expectedly incorporate two intact acetate units, indicative of fungal mode F cyclisation. Three other members of this group (TW93c, TW93d and TW93e) have typical C-7/C-12 mode S cyclised initial rings; congener TW93h was assigned a unique adamantane structure, with a novel C-13/C-18-bridged initial ring. This mix of F and S folding modes was plausibly attributed to catalysis by an engineered streptomycete type II iterative PKS with relaxed regiospecificity of crosslinking. Conceivably this could lead to formation of both mode-F- and mode-S-cy- clised products. The production of this mixture by recombinant enzymes would not contravene the current general biosynthet- ic rule, as this was proposed as a cyclisation characteristic of microbial wild-type synthases (not necessarily of mutant syn- thases).

The unanticipated formation of the atypical mode-F-cyclised dodecaketides TW93f and TW93g is possibly due to incorrect assignment of their original structures as 25 and 26.[11] The al- ternative isomeric structures (27 and 28; Scheme 6) contain, respectively, C-7/C-12 and C-9/C-14 mode S crosslinked initial rings, consistent with the requirements of the proposed bio- synthetic classification of streptomycete fused-ring PKs. Un- fortunately, the validity of this option cannot be evaluated, as the relevant spectroscopic data and the originally isolated compounds are unavailable.[36] In addition to the putative biosynthesis of fused-ring PKs by iterative type I PKSs of fungi (e.g., chrysophanol 4) and type II PKSs of bacteria (e.g., chrysophanol 5), the formation of fused- ring dodecaketides by type III PKSs has also been described.[37] Type III PKS are predominantly of plant origin and catalyse the formation a wide diversity of structures ranging from common chalcones and stilbenes[38, 39] to the less abundant curcumi- noids[40] and phenylphenalenones.[41, 42]

Of particular interest regarding the origin of the assigned atypical mode-F-cyclised streptomycete dodecaketide struc- tures of TW93f (25) and TW93g (26) was the finding by Wani- buchi et al.[43] that the F66L/N222G double mutation of a type III PKS of the plant Aloe arborescens appeared to result in an increase in the volume of its synthase active-site cavity, thus leading to formation of the C24 naphtho-g-pyrone dodecake- tide TW95a (29). This is a known product of the minimal type II whiE PKS of S. coelicolor, which is closely related to the sug- gested alternative structure, 28, for TW93g. In theory, TW95a could form from 28 by elimination of a molecule of water from C-7 and C-8, together with enolisation of C-15 and conse- quent aromatisation. Piloquinone 30 (Scheme 7; also 34, R = isobutyl) is the principal pigment of Streptomyces pilosus and was isolated in 1963 by Lederer and co-workers.[44] It was identified as a member of the rare group of streptomycete phenanthraquinones, which include murayaquinone 35 (R = ethyl)[27] and haloquinone 36 (R = H).[28] The structure of piloquinone has been confirmed by synthesis,[45] as has that of its naturally occurring analogue 4- hydroxypiloquinone.[46] Feeding studies with 14C-labelled potential precursors en- abled Lederer et al. to confirm the derivation of piloquinone from acetate, isobutyrate and valine; neither methionine, pro- pionate nor mevalonic acid was incorporated.[47] These obser- vations supported a biosynthetic pathway based on an isobu- tyrate starter unit and nine acetate extender units, but preclud- ed the precursors propionate, or methionine proposed by Birch.[48] (cid:2) 2016 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. KGaA, Weinheim Scheme 7. Phenanthroquinone by A) mode F and B) mode S biosynthetic options. a) elimination of 6-OH and 15-OH; b) C-14 ketonisn and aromatisn. The S. pilosus mechanism proposed by the Lederer group (Scheme 7 A) necessitates the incorporation by of two adjacent intact acetate units in the initially formed ring and requires C- 8/C-13 crosslinking. This corresponds to a fungal mode-F path- way rather than that of a streptomycete mode-S-fused ring PK, and would be inconsistent with the fused-ring biosynthetic rule.

A possible alternative mechanism for the formation of pilo- quinone by mode-S cyclisation is shown in Scheme 7 B. This predicts rearrangement of an intermediate fused-ring anthra- quinone epoxide 31 with two successive carbon 1,2-shifts. It employs the same isobutyrate starter unit and nine acetate or malonate extender units (as in the Lederer scheme), but uses a mode-S-folded anthraquinone intermediate as the source of the initial ring, which is C-7/C-12 crosslinked. The terminal ace- tate-derived extender unit is incorporated as C-1 and C-2 of the epoxide; this ring opens, loses C-1 by decarboxylation and rearrangement to form 32. An analogous pathway could supply the Streptomyces mur- ayamaensis corre- sponding to the [13C2]acetate-derived labelling pattern 35 (R = ChemBioChem 2016, 17, 1 – 9 phenanthraquinone murayaquinone,[11] ethyl) reported by Gould et al.[27] The two successive carbon 1,2-shifts leading to intermediates 32 and 33 are in principle equivalent to C-15 of 31 undergoing a single 1,3-shift to C-6 of 33. Isotopic precursor labelling or other experimental studies might establish some details of the elimination pathways. It also allows possible formation of either C-6 or C-15 single hy- droxyl elimination products, which consequently might occur as co-metabolites in extracts of the parent fungus. Another ap- proach would involve feeding of advanced isotopically labelled synthetic intermediates (structurally related to possible precur- sors of the postulated anthraquinone intermediate 31).

Haloquinone 36 (R = H) was isolated from Streptomyces vene- zuelae and was structurally characterised by Zeeck and col- leagues;[28] they suggested a PK mechanism analogous to the piloquinone pathway proposed by Lederer et al. (Scheme 7 A). The alternative mode S cyclisation pathways to piloquinone 34, murayaquinone 35 and haloquinone 36 differ only in the bio- synthetic origins of the starter group (Scheme 7 B). In the case of haloquinone, as the starter unit of the intermediate nonake- tide anthraquinone epoxide 31(R = H) is acetate, the resulting phenanthraquinone corresponds to a rearranged and decar- boxylated nonaketide. The latter postulated epoxyanthraquinone pathway uses two successive 1,2-shifts and leads to phenanthraquinones; it is allied to the previously proposed epoxide-driven rearrange- ment involved in the biosynthesis of the spiro mode-S-folded (40; fused-ring Scheme 8).[42, 49, 50] Based on [13C2]acetate feeding studies, 40 was initially thought to form from two PK chains.[49a] Subse- quently, a single linear-chain pathway was proposed, involving two sequential 1,2-shifts of a mode-S-folded epoxypentadeca- ketide 31 to form the spiro intermediate 32.[49b] The latter was recovered from Streptomyces griseus by Chen et al. and named fredericamycin E.[51] The earlier fredericamycin A proposal[49b] was cited by Gould et al. in their study of the origin of muraya- quinone and led to the suggestion of a further pathway.[27]

Although piloquinone, murayaquinone and haloquinone contain phenanthraquinone units, there does not appear to be any evidence for the formation of this tricyclic angular fused- ring moiety in streptomycete metabolites through direct mode-S or mode-F cyclisation of a linear PK precursor. The only proposal for such a pathway is that made by Birch and Smith in 1958[52] for the biosynthesis of denticulatol 37. This product was isolated as a congener of the PK anthraquinone chysophanol from roots of the plant Rumex chinesis. However, the assigned structure of denticulatol proved be inconsistent with the subsequent synthetic studies by Sargent and Smith.[53] One of the most complex known sequences of polyketide fused-ring cleavage and side-chain rearrangements is that leading to the highly carcinogenic aflatoxins produced by the fungus Aspergillus flavus; these were identified in 1960 as the source of Turkey X disease. In 1965, I suggested[54] that oxida- tive ring-cleavage of anthraquinone intermediates could pro- vide a plausible mechanism for the origin of a major part of the aflatoxin nucleus and its fungal xanthone congener sterig- matocystin (42),[55] which was viewed as a likely precursor of aflatoxin B1 (43).[1, 56] It was subsequently proposed that the bis- (cid:2) 2016 Wiley-VCH Verlag GmbH & Co. This speculative pathway is in keeping with the results of subsequent chemical, enzymatic, genetic and isotopically la- belled precursor feeding studies;[17, 58–63] these have not provid- ed evidence for any exceptions to the proposed generalisation that two unrelated classes of microorganisms utilise different F and S modes of cyclisation. 5. Conclusion and Outlook In some instances, the search for F or S exceptions has necessi- tated revision of accepted structural assignments or reappraisal of credible alternative mechanisms for their biosynthesis. It has also highlighted a difference between the biosynthesis of fused-ring and monobenzenoid polyketides, associated with different modes of PKS hydrogen bonding. Although this concept paper has not provided evidence that conflicts with the predicted F and S modes of folding of fused- ring polyketides, some candidate exceptions require structural or biosynthetic revisions. In the absence of [13C2]acetate feed- ing studies, such inclusions should be regarded as speculative or hypothetical. Further consideration of such interrelationships might facili- tate the design and production of antimetabolites, antitumour agents or other potentially useful products, for example selec- tive inhibitors of ring fissions or rearrangements involved in the production of aflatoxins.[64] Some successful preliminary in- ChemBioChem 2016, 17, 1 – 9 These are not the final page numbers!
